Your first SparkSession.

Everything you do in Spark starts from a SparkSession. It is your handle to the engine — you use it to read data, to register views, and to run queries.

To run locally, you need java seventeen or newer installed. Then you pip install pyspark, version three point five point three.

The pattern is the same every time. You build a session from the builder, you give it an app name, you point it at a master — for us that is local mode — and you call get-or-create. The object it returns is your entry point to everything Spark can do.

Now, one key gotcha, and it catches people constantly. Get-or-create is sticky. If a SparkSession already exists in your kernel — maybe from an earlier cell, maybe from a previous notebook, anywhere at all — the builder returns that existing session, and it silently ignores the new configuration you just set. To pick up new configuration in a running notebook, you have to call spark dot stop first, and then build again.
